Raw dev notes -- RAG Pipeline: Taming the Data Beast (and My Sanity)

Alright, another sprint down on the RAG knowledge base pipeline. This project is essentially my attempt to build a robust, automated system for ingesting various data sources – think chat logs, internal articles, etc. – processing them, and then deploying them into a format that our RAG models can actually use. The goal is to keep our models up-to-date with the latest info without me having to manually babysit every single piece of content. It's all about making our AI smarter and more current.

This past week or so has been a whirlwind of getting the deployment side of things really solid. I finally got the `sync_and_deploy` orchestrator humming, which is a huge milestone. It's the brain that pulls everything together, from processing new WhatsApp chunks (yeah, still wrestling with those) and stripping out irrelevant comment threads from articles, to adding speaker tags to make conversations more useful. A big win was integrating the `chatwrapper` for auto-deploying those "mega-files" – honestly, dealing with large files always feels like a mini-boss battle.

But man, it wasn't all smooth sailing. The biggest headache, by far, was getting the data integrity right during deployment. I spent way too much time chasing down "stale sources" that were somehow replacing valid ones, or vice-versa. The `ID-diff verification of upload + verified delete` commit was a direct result of that nightmare. It's one thing to upload new data, it's another to ensure that when you *update* data, you're not accidentally creating orphans or bringing back old ghosts. That whole process of verifying what's actually changed and what needs to be deleted was way more complex than I anticipated. I also had to fix an `orphan sweep` issue in the orchestrator, which was just adding to the general feeling of "is this thing actually cleaning up after itself?"

Another classic "why didn't I think of this earlier?" moment was the WhatsApp date format fix. Turns out, people export their chats in different locales, so my script was choking on Hebrew date formats. Had to add support for both D.M.YYYY and M/D/YY. It's a small thing, but it's those little real-world data quirks that always bite you. And then, of course, making the whole deployment process more resilient with retries, missing-source reconciliation, and `is_ready` polls – because nothing ever deploys perfectly on the first try, right?

Honestly, this period felt like I was less building new features and more shoring up the foundations. It was frustrating at times, especially when I felt like I was just fixing my own previous mistakes or overlooking obvious edge cases. But there's a real sense of satisfaction in making something truly robust. It's a reminder that the "boring" work of error handling, data integrity, and proper orchestration is often the most critical. It feels like I'm growing past just getting things to *work* and moving towards making them *reliable* and *maintainable*. The `setup.sh` and `setup_scheduled_task.ps1` for fresh machine bootstrap also felt good – finally making it easy for someone (or future me) to get this thing running from scratch.

Next up: Really stress-testing that ID-diff under real-world data drift.
